My name's Kim Yannon.

01:09:05.910 --> 01:09:08.729
I'm currently doing some Public
Health, Health Care Delivery

01:09:08.729 --> 01:09:09.979
research at MIT.

01:09:09.979 --> 01:09:12.359
Recent graduate of
Michigan State University,

01:09:12.359 --> 01:09:14.520
actually, so go green.

01:09:14.520 --> 01:09:17.399
Go white.

01:09:17.399 --> 01:09:21.149
So-- and in the wake of
things that have been going

01:09:21.149 --> 01:09:23.340
on at Michigan
State University--

01:09:23.340 --> 01:09:24.990
the heartbreaking,
heartbreaking,

01:09:24.990 --> 01:09:27.569
heartbreaking failure
of the institution

01:09:27.569 --> 01:09:32.040
to address the Larry
Nassar crisis --I'm really

01:09:32.040 --> 01:09:36.149
on board with the things you've
been saying about standing firm

01:09:36.149 --> 01:09:40.109
with our ideals against
institutions that have

01:09:40.109 --> 01:09:44.520
blatantly disregarded some
of the most vulnerable people

01:09:44.520 --> 01:09:48.500
that they're charged with
protecting and taking care of.

01:09:48.500 --> 01:09:52.920
So, speaking to your
public health record,

01:09:52.920 --> 01:09:54.570
you mentioned, kind
of, the phrase,

01:09:54.570 --> 01:09:56.320
like, forming
unlikely partnerships,

01:09:56.320 --> 01:09:59.770
which is actually a really big
buzz phrase in public health.

01:09:59.770 --> 01:10:02.180
In fact, the Harvard Chan
School of Public Health

01:10:02.180 --> 01:10:04.200
just hosted the
Surgeon General, who

01:10:04.200 --> 01:10:05.670
used a similar
phrase when he was

01:10:05.670 --> 01:10:07.760
talking about his prerogatives.

01:10:07.760 --> 01:10:09.180
So can you speak
a little bit more

01:10:09.180 --> 01:10:14.280
to exactly how maybe reaching
out to an unlikely partner who

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:19.450
may have a lot of disagreements,
in terms of other values,

01:10:19.450 --> 01:10:22.230
interests, maybe even
political affiliations,

01:10:22.230 --> 01:10:24.960
and how do you identify
those partners.

01:10:24.960 --> 01:10:30.780
How do you kind of
incentivize, like,

01:10:30.780 --> 01:10:34.200
an alignment of values, and
laying out, like, OK, this

01:10:34.200 --> 01:10:36.300
is valuable to you,
too, and really getting

01:10:36.300 --> 01:10:37.800
on the same page with that.

01:10:37.800 --> 01:10:38.940
- Thank you.

01:10:38.940 --> 01:10:40.890
So first, I just
have to say that

01:10:40.890 --> 01:10:46.590
the massive failure at MSU--

01:10:46.590 --> 01:10:49.710
I hate to say it, it's just
one of the most heartbreaking

01:10:49.710 --> 01:10:53.760
things that I watched develop.

01:10:53.760 --> 01:10:57.750
And you think about the courage
of those women to come up

01:10:57.750 --> 01:11:00.990
and to say their truth.

01:11:00.990 --> 01:11:04.590
I just think that we need
more courage like that.

01:11:04.590 --> 01:11:06.660
And the other side of
this that often gets

01:11:06.660 --> 01:11:09.810
missed in the
conversation about MSU,

01:11:09.810 --> 01:11:12.270
and frankly, the conversation
about the Me Too movement,

01:11:12.270 --> 01:11:13.890
is the culpability
and responsibility

01:11:13.890 --> 01:11:19.530
of men to reach out and to
be a part of breaking down

01:11:19.530 --> 01:11:22.950
a culture of sexual violence
and toxic masculinity

01:11:22.950 --> 01:11:25.620
that we've allowed to
pervade our institutions

01:11:25.620 --> 01:11:28.140
and our culture for
far too long now.

01:11:28.140 --> 01:11:31.800
And if this is not a wake
up call for men to stand up

01:11:31.800 --> 01:11:37.647
and to speak about these issues,
and to engage on these issues,

01:11:37.647 --> 01:11:38.730
I don't know what will be.

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:43.020
And my hope is that men, as
a function of the courage

01:11:43.020 --> 01:11:45.870
of women to stand up and
call this what it is,

01:11:45.870 --> 01:11:49.830
will be willing to take this and
do the work that they uniquely

01:11:49.830 --> 01:11:53.410
can do around being able
to call this out everywhere

01:11:53.410 --> 01:11:54.390
we see it, right.

01:11:54.390 --> 01:11:57.990
You know, this concept
of locker room talk

01:11:57.990 --> 01:12:03.410
came out of the President's
piss poor attempt

01:12:03.410 --> 01:12:08.270
to try and justify the things
that he said about women.

01:12:08.270 --> 01:12:09.890
But locker room talk
is a real thing.

01:12:09.890 --> 01:12:13.520
And if we're not willing to have
a conversation with a young man

01:12:13.520 --> 01:12:16.580
who's talking about
objectifying a woman,

01:12:16.580 --> 01:12:19.520
then the question becomes,
did we enable something?

01:12:19.520 --> 01:12:21.770
And I think that's where the
locus of the conversation

01:12:21.770 --> 01:12:23.120
needs to go.

01:12:23.120 --> 01:12:27.557
So about unlikely partnerships.

01:12:27.557 --> 01:12:30.140
One of the things that, I think,
is really important for folks

01:12:30.140 --> 01:12:32.720
who aspire to leadership
to remind themselves

01:12:32.720 --> 01:12:35.090
is that leadership is
not just about finding

01:12:35.090 --> 01:12:36.260
the world as it is.

01:12:36.260 --> 01:12:40.320
It's about creating the world
as you believe it should be.

01:12:40.320 --> 01:12:44.960
And, oftentimes, it means
being very vocal and honest

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:47.540
about the values that
animate your work,

01:12:47.540 --> 01:12:50.304
and then watching as
people will align to what

01:12:50.304 --> 01:12:51.470
you're talking about, right.

01:12:51.470 --> 01:12:54.171
Great political
leadership is not just--

01:12:54.171 --> 01:12:56.420
we'll say effective political
leadership --is not just

01:12:56.420 --> 01:12:59.460
about being able to find what
people are talking about.

01:12:59.460 --> 01:13:01.460
It's about being
able to dictate,

01:13:01.460 --> 01:13:03.620
in some way, what the
conversation ought

01:13:03.620 --> 01:13:05.070
to be able to move forward.

01:13:05.070 --> 01:13:07.160
And I'll use a very bad
example of this just

01:13:07.160 --> 01:13:08.930
to see how effective it was.

01:13:08.930 --> 01:13:10.850
Polling showed that
immigration was not

01:13:10.850 --> 01:13:12.380
even on the top-10
list of issues

01:13:12.380 --> 01:13:14.510
going into the 2016 election.

01:13:14.510 --> 01:13:17.180
But the current person
who is president now

01:13:17.180 --> 01:13:19.700
was able to make
that an issue, right.

01:13:19.700 --> 01:13:20.630
Build the wall.

01:13:20.630 --> 01:13:22.730
It's a solution
to a non-problem.

01:13:22.730 --> 01:13:25.220
But, by making a solution
to a non-problem,

01:13:25.220 --> 01:13:26.560
he turned it into a problem.

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:27.600
Does that makes sense?

01:13:27.600 --> 01:13:30.500
And we have to remind
ourselves that, as leaders, we

01:13:30.500 --> 01:13:33.320
have the ability to move
the public conversation,

01:13:33.320 --> 01:13:35.990
not just to find the
conversation where it is.

01:13:35.990 --> 01:13:38.030
And what that means is
that, when people see you

01:13:38.030 --> 01:13:42.590
as being a credible believer in
the things that you care about,

01:13:42.590 --> 01:13:45.080
they'll sometimes
find you in ways

01:13:45.080 --> 01:13:46.770
that you wouldn't have expected.

01:13:46.770 --> 01:13:49.144
One of the things that I
learned at the Health Department

01:13:49.144 --> 01:13:51.590
was exactly this, was
when we were trying

01:13:51.590 --> 01:13:54.800
to move on certain issues,
we found that, oftentimes,

01:13:54.800 --> 01:13:57.560
some of the small business
organizations in southwest

01:13:57.560 --> 01:13:59.810
Detroit, when we were
advocating against Marathon,

01:13:59.810 --> 01:14:01.201
they were our
biggest supporters.

01:14:01.201 --> 01:14:01.700
Why?

01:14:01.700 --> 01:14:05.090
Because they have to live
in that world where the air

01:14:05.090 --> 01:14:06.399
is so poisoned.

01:14:06.399 --> 01:14:07.940
They wouldn't be
the natural partner.

01:14:07.940 --> 01:14:09.680
But because you're
standing up on something,

01:14:09.680 --> 01:14:11.410
they're saying, you know,
that's an issue for me, too.

01:14:11.410 --> 01:14:12.560
And I'm going to
be a part of this.

01:14:12.560 --> 01:14:14.540
Even though, traditionally,
they're saying, well,

01:14:14.540 --> 01:14:15.680
why are you regulating
on business?

01:14:15.680 --> 01:14:16.670
Why are you telling
business what to do,

01:14:16.670 --> 01:14:18.294
et cetera, et cetera,
et cetera, right.

01:14:18.294 --> 01:14:22.880
And so I think it's about, more
than anything else, believing

01:14:22.880 --> 01:14:24.710
in the values that
you bring forward,

01:14:24.710 --> 01:14:27.320
and the actions that
those values necessitate,

01:14:27.320 --> 01:14:29.570
and then being
willing to touch hands

01:14:29.570 --> 01:14:32.600
with people who sometimes
might come out of the woodwork,

01:14:32.600 --> 01:14:33.290
right.

01:14:33.290 --> 01:14:34.664
And then the other
thing about it

01:14:34.664 --> 01:14:36.830
is being willing
to say that there

01:14:36.830 --> 01:14:39.770
is no such thing as an enemy.

01:14:39.770 --> 01:14:42.860
There is such a thing as
opposing the wrong action

01:14:42.860 --> 01:14:44.750
in a particular moment.

01:14:44.750 --> 01:14:46.370
And the willingness
to say, we're

01:14:46.370 --> 01:14:49.640
going to be about
values, rather than being

01:14:49.640 --> 01:14:54.500
about traditional enemy
versus friend alliances,

01:14:54.500 --> 01:14:56.666
allows you then to be very
thoughtful about being

01:14:56.666 --> 01:14:58.790
able to pick partnerships
across the various things

01:14:58.790 --> 01:15:01.467
that you work on, because you
are credible on the issues

01:15:01.467 --> 01:15:02.300
that you care about.

01:15:02.300 --> 01:15:03.830
I think, more than
anything else,

01:15:03.830 --> 01:15:05.270
people look for
partners that are

01:15:05.270 --> 01:15:07.250
firm on what they believe in.

01:15:07.250 --> 01:15:09.690
Because they don't
want to be shown,

01:15:09.690 --> 01:15:13.550
you know, for being unable
to move the world the way

01:15:13.550 --> 01:15:14.700
they want to move it.

01:15:14.700 --> 01:15:16.725
So being able to say,
this is what I believe in,

01:15:16.725 --> 01:15:19.100
this is how I believe in it,
and this how I fight for it.

01:15:19.100 --> 01:15:21.950
Keep a big smile on my face, and
we're going to move forward--

01:15:21.950 --> 01:15:23.450
you'll find that people
come out of the woodwork

01:15:23.450 --> 01:15:25.259
and will want to work
with you on things,

01:15:25.259 --> 01:15:27.050
and in partnerships
you would never expect.

01:15:27.050 --> 01:15:29.990
And I think it's being
firm on what you believe,

01:15:29.990 --> 01:15:32.484
driving forward on the
action that necessitates,

01:15:32.484 --> 01:15:34.400
and then being willing
to partner with anybody

01:15:34.400 --> 01:15:36.899
and everybody who wants to get
that thing done-- recognizing

01:15:36.899 --> 01:15:40.040
that in the next iteration,
you might not be partners.

01:15:40.040 --> 01:15:42.790
But hey, that's
the world, right.

01:15:42.790 --> 01:15:45.124
- Thank you

01:15:45.124 --> 01:15:46.670
- Hey, I'm Amanda Markovitz.

01:15:46.670 --> 01:15:48.560
I'm a doctoral student
in epidemiology

01:15:48.560 --> 01:15:50.060
and a former Michigander.

01:15:50.060 --> 01:15:50.660
- All right.

01:15:50.660 --> 01:15:51.920
You want to come back?

01:15:51.920 --> 01:15:53.789
We need epidemiologists.

01:15:53.789 --> 01:15:54.830
- Yeah, I had a question.

01:15:54.830 --> 01:15:57.170
So, you know, we talk a
lot about the disconnect

01:15:57.170 --> 01:15:58.790
between science and politics.

01:15:58.790 --> 01:16:01.555
And I'm so glad that
you're bridging that gap,

01:16:01.555 --> 01:16:03.680
and especially that you're
talking about statistics

01:16:03.680 --> 01:16:05.420
in a way that reaches
people, and talking

01:16:05.420 --> 01:16:07.820
about these stories
and anecdotes that

01:16:07.820 --> 01:16:09.120
really matter to people.

01:16:09.120 --> 01:16:13.010
And I wonder if you have other
lessons for us scientists that

01:16:13.010 --> 01:16:15.950
are trying to communicate
with our communities-- maybe

01:16:15.950 --> 01:16:18.830
not running for Governor, but
on a smaller level --and ways

01:16:18.830 --> 01:16:20.080
that we can do a better job.

01:16:20.080 --> 01:16:20.960
- Yeah.

01:16:20.960 --> 01:16:22.760
So first of all, do it.

01:16:22.760 --> 01:16:25.940
You know, a lot of scientists--

01:16:25.940 --> 01:16:28.080
the incentives that
exist in academia

01:16:28.080 --> 01:16:31.107
sometimes preclude
well-meaning scientists

01:16:31.107 --> 01:16:33.690
who want their work to move the
public conversation from doing

01:16:33.690 --> 01:16:36.967
it, because it's
not what's rewarded.

01:16:36.967 --> 01:16:39.300
And I honestly think that's
a big problem with academia,

01:16:39.300 --> 01:16:41.430
and one of the things we
all need to fix, right.

01:16:41.430 --> 01:16:42.240
Let's be clear.

01:16:42.240 --> 01:16:45.120
If your work is not actually
moving the public conversation,

01:16:45.120 --> 01:16:47.880
then what's it moving--
especially in epi,

01:16:47.880 --> 01:16:49.470
especially when so
much of what we do

01:16:49.470 --> 01:16:56.310
is about misaligned actions
of institutions, right.

01:16:56.310 --> 01:16:59.572
So be the courageous one in the
institution who communicates,

01:16:59.572 --> 01:17:00.780
who gets your work out there.

01:17:00.780 --> 01:17:03.600
Don't just write the paper,
write the op-ed, right.

01:17:03.600 --> 01:17:04.620
That's number one.

01:17:04.620 --> 01:17:10.830
Number two, oftentimes
the difference

01:17:10.830 --> 01:17:14.850
in the ways that scientists
communicate versus policy

01:17:14.850 --> 01:17:17.530
people communicate
allow the conversations

01:17:17.530 --> 01:17:18.780
to miss each other in the air.

01:17:18.780 --> 01:17:22.620
So scientists always ask,
what's not known, right.

01:17:22.620 --> 01:17:24.420
That's the question:
what's not known?

01:17:24.420 --> 01:17:28.230
And then, how do I get to making
a known out of an unknown.

01:17:28.230 --> 01:17:30.480
Right, that's like
the push for science.

01:17:30.480 --> 01:17:32.670
Policy people
aren't asking what's

01:17:32.670 --> 01:17:34.896
not known, they're
asking, what are

01:17:34.896 --> 01:17:36.270
the implications
of what is known

01:17:36.270 --> 01:17:37.555
for what I can do right now?

01:17:37.555 --> 01:17:38.840
Do you see what I mean.

01:17:38.840 --> 01:17:41.424
And I think it's on both of them
to be able to translate well,

01:17:41.424 --> 01:17:43.631
right, because most of the
time, if you have a policy

01:17:43.631 --> 01:17:45.480
person who's not
trained in science,

01:17:45.480 --> 01:17:48.236
they're always asking why the
scientist keeps putting caveats

01:17:48.236 --> 01:17:49.360
behind what they're saying.

01:17:49.360 --> 01:17:53.160
Because most science would
be like, this is the--

01:17:53.160 --> 01:17:56.730
my work's suggesting-- like
last paragraph of every paper,

01:17:56.730 --> 01:18:00.510
right --this work suggests
that opportunities

01:18:00.510 --> 01:18:02.050
for future research
look like this.

01:18:02.050 --> 01:18:04.830
You're like, no no no, what
does this mean for the world?

01:18:04.830 --> 01:18:06.780
And a lot of
scientists will always

01:18:06.780 --> 01:18:09.670
caveat what they
tell you they think

01:18:09.670 --> 01:18:13.950
should happen based on the best,
most rigorous work out there.

01:18:13.950 --> 01:18:15.450
And if scientists
themselves who are

01:18:15.450 --> 01:18:16.810
doing the best,
most rigorous work

01:18:16.810 --> 01:18:19.309
aren't willing to give you a
firm answer, then at some point

01:18:19.309 --> 01:18:21.790
you're like, meh,
nobody knows anything.

01:18:21.790 --> 01:18:22.690
I'm serious.

01:18:22.690 --> 01:18:25.150
And so part of what scientists
need to be able to do

01:18:25.150 --> 01:18:27.880
is speak like policy
people do, which is to say,

01:18:27.880 --> 01:18:30.320
of the current
opportunities that exist,

01:18:30.320 --> 01:18:32.792
this is the one
that would create

01:18:32.792 --> 01:18:34.750
x outcome that you are
interested in maximizing

01:18:34.750 --> 01:18:35.458
your policymaker.

01:18:35.458 --> 01:18:36.520
See what I mean?

01:18:36.520 --> 01:18:38.770
So being able to
speak that language.

01:18:38.770 --> 01:18:42.760
And then, one of the
interesting thing things

01:18:42.760 --> 01:18:46.210
that I've come to
appreciate about science

01:18:46.210 --> 01:18:53.190
is that we often get
so focused on methods,

01:18:53.190 --> 01:18:57.210
and the way of knowing, and
the epistemology of the thing

01:18:57.210 --> 01:19:01.960
that we get sidetracked from
issues that actually matter,

01:19:01.960 --> 01:19:04.340
and actually change
facts on the ground.

01:19:04.340 --> 01:19:06.640
And I would encourage
any young scientist

01:19:06.640 --> 01:19:11.440
who wants their work to shape
the public conversation--

01:19:11.440 --> 01:19:14.740
or even more importantly,
public policy --to ask,

01:19:14.740 --> 01:19:17.320
every question that
you ask as a scientist,

01:19:17.320 --> 01:19:20.110
ask yourself what the policy
analog of this should be.

01:19:20.110 --> 01:19:21.736
What does this suggest
about the world.

01:19:21.736 --> 01:19:23.776
And if you don't have a
good answer, that's fine.

01:19:23.776 --> 01:19:24.700
You don't have to yet.

01:19:24.700 --> 01:19:28.547
But remember, policymakers are
constantly making decisions.

01:19:28.547 --> 01:19:30.880
We don't have the luxury of
waiting for future research.

01:19:30.880 --> 01:19:32.004
Do you see what I'm saying?

01:19:32.004 --> 01:19:34.690
And so if you recognize
that to be the case,

01:19:34.690 --> 01:19:38.512
and you know that your
work can animate something,

01:19:38.512 --> 01:19:39.970
then I think it is
a responsibility

01:19:39.970 --> 01:19:42.400
to stand up and say, I know.

01:19:42.400 --> 01:19:45.940
I'll say this, as a
professor, I always

01:19:45.940 --> 01:19:48.940
knew that my PhD students
were ready to graduate

01:19:48.940 --> 01:19:53.286
when they could comfortably
say, I don't know.

01:19:53.286 --> 01:19:54.910
Because I think the
exercise of getting

01:19:54.910 --> 01:19:58.690
a PhD is becoming comfortable
with the vastness of knowledge,

01:19:58.690 --> 01:20:00.940
and what you actually don't
know about that knowledge,

01:20:00.940 --> 01:20:03.190
right, what are the
bounds of your expertise.

01:20:03.190 --> 01:20:06.250
And the problem with
that is that most people

01:20:06.250 --> 01:20:07.730
don't think that way.

01:20:07.730 --> 01:20:09.790
Most people, and the
nature of ignorance,

01:20:09.790 --> 01:20:12.160
is to claim knowledge, and
the nature of knowledge

01:20:12.160 --> 01:20:14.660
is to claim ignorance.

01:20:14.660 --> 01:20:15.282
Right.

01:20:15.282 --> 01:20:16.740
And if you think
about it that way,

01:20:16.740 --> 01:20:20.120
that's why we have a bunch of
really ignorant policymakers

01:20:20.120 --> 01:20:25.130
making decisions, and scientists
being like, I'm not sure.

01:20:25.130 --> 01:20:26.780
And so when you
recognize that that's

01:20:26.780 --> 01:20:29.210
just the social pressure
behind what you do,

01:20:29.210 --> 01:20:31.820
there's a responsibility to
be able to step up and say,

01:20:31.820 --> 01:20:32.630
actually, I do--

01:20:32.630 --> 01:20:38.350
I know a lot more than you do,
and to call it how you see it.

01:20:38.350 --> 01:20:40.362
Truth has a moral
implication to it.

01:20:40.362 --> 01:20:42.070
And the last thing
I'll say on this issue

01:20:42.070 --> 01:20:45.670
is that we have sort
of devoided science

01:20:45.670 --> 01:20:49.090
from the moral
imperative for truth.

01:20:49.090 --> 01:20:51.950
And if we believe
something to be true,

01:20:51.950 --> 01:20:53.710
then it has actionable
responsibility

01:20:53.710 --> 01:20:55.120
that comes with it.

01:20:55.120 --> 01:20:58.570
And our failure to action
to make that actionable--

01:20:58.570 --> 01:21:00.220
that carries more weight.

01:21:00.220 --> 01:21:02.470
And I think there
is a responsibility

01:21:02.470 --> 01:21:05.650
for the community to come
to grips with the fact

01:21:05.650 --> 01:21:08.530
that we don't want to be
doing science in a vacuum--

01:21:08.530 --> 01:21:10.570
because we're not doing
science in a vacuum.

01:21:10.570 --> 01:21:13.900
And the world right now, when
it comes to good information,

01:21:13.900 --> 01:21:15.141
